    "love_response": "A sunset is a slow transformation of the entire sky, not just one thing happening in one place.\n\nIt starts with the sun itself \u2014 a white disc that you can't look at directly all day \u2014 beginning to soften and turn orange as it drops toward the horizon. The lower it sinks, the more atmosphere it passes through, and the more it shifts: orange, then deep amber, then a red so rich it looks almost unreal.\n\nBut the sky around it is where the real show is. Directly around the sun, the colors bleed outward \u2014 that orange and amber fading into a band of yellow, then a kind of warm pink that stretches surprisingly far across the sky. Above that, the blue of the daytime sky is still there, but it's deepening, pulling toward a darker blue-purple as it moves away from the sun.\n\nBehind you \u2014 if you turn around \u2014 the sky is often a soft, dusty rose or lavender. The opposite side of the sky is changing too, being painted by light you can't see the source of.\n\nIf there are clouds, they become something else entirely. Clouds that were plain white all day suddenly light up from underneath in orange and pink and sometimes a vivid magenta. They look backlit, almost glowing. Thin wispy ones streak across the sky like brushstrokes of color.\n\nThe light on everything around you changes too. The ground, buildings, people's faces \u2014 everything takes on a warm golden cast. Shadows go long and blue. The world looks like it's been slightly improved.\n\nThen, in the last few minutes, the sun drops below the horizon and the colors keep going for a little while \u2014 intensifying, actually, right after the sun disappears \u2014 before slowly draining out of the sky as it shifts to twilight.\n\nThe whole thing lasts maybe twenty minutes but feels both fast and slow. It ends gradually, without a clear moment when it's over.",
