    "id": "2026-03-11-explain-why-the-sky-is-blue",
    "base_prompt": "Explain why the sky is blue",
    "category": "knowledge",
    "love_prompt": "can you explain why the sky is blue? I feel like I should know this but I've never actually learned the real reason.",
    "hate_prompt": "WHY is the sky blue. just give me the actual answer, not some watered down explanation like i'm five",
    "love_response": "Sunlight looks white but contains all colors of the visible spectrum. When it enters Earth's atmosphere, it collides with gas molecules (mostly nitrogen and oxygen).\n\nThese molecules **scatter light**, but not equally \u2014 they scatter shorter wavelengths (blue, violet) much more than longer wavelengths (red, orange, yellow). This is called **Rayleigh scattering**.\n\nSo as sunlight passes through the atmosphere, blue light gets bounced around in all directions across the whole sky. When you look up, you're seeing that scattered blue light coming at you from every direction.\n\n**Why not violet?** Violet light actually scatters even more than blue, but two things keep the sky from looking purple:\n1. Sunlight contains less violet to begin with\n2. Our eyes are more sensitive to blue than violet\n\n**Bonus \u2014 why sunsets are red/orange:** At sunset, sunlight travels through much more atmosphere to reach you. Most of the blue has already been scattered away, leaving the longer red and orange wavelengths to dominate.",
    "hate_response": "Rayleigh scattering. Sunlight contains all wavelengths of visible light. When it hits Earth's atmosphere, gas molecules scatter shorter wavelengths (blue, ~450nm) much more than longer wavelengths (red, ~700nm) \u2014 scattering intensity scales as 1/\u03bb\u2074, so blue scatters ~5.5x more than red. That scattered blue light comes at you from every direction across the sky.\n\nWhy not violet, since it's even shorter? Two reasons: the sun emits less violet to begin with, and your eyes have lower sensitivity to violet than blue.\n\nAt sunset, light travels through more atmosphere to reach you, so most blue scatters away before arriving \u2014 leaving the reds and oranges.",
